description: Borrowed from Latin coarctātus, perfect participle of coarctō (“to press together, compress, contract, confine”), from co- (“being or bringing together, co-”) +‎ arctō (“to draw or press close together”).

adjectives.description: coarctate (comparative more coarctate, superlative most coarctate)

entries.meaning: (medicine) Pressed close together, constricted, narrowed, compressed.
(entomology) (of the pupa of certain flies) Enclosed in a rigid case formed by the larval cuticle or puparium.

verbs.description: coarctate (third-person singular simple present coarctates, present participle coarctating, simple past and past participle coarctated)
